ltn1 ubiquitylates tyw3 and rsk1/2 in a regulatory manner.
as such, loss of ltn1 may result in unrestrained rsk1/2 activity during mapk signaling and may drive translation during conditions that would otherwise restrain protein production.
our data suggest that regulatory, nondegradative ltn1 mediated ubiquitylation inhibits rsk1/2 activity.
ltn1 ubiquitylation of rsk1, rsk2, and twy3 could either result in degradation or impart a regulatory function on target proteins distinct from degradation.
taken together, our results indicate that ltn1 can ubiquitylate rsk1, rsk2, and tyw3, and this ubiquitylation does not function to target these proteins for degradation.
